There is a working example of calling a C routine from a FORTRAN
routine. The C routine generates a gaussian random field and 
passes it back to the FORTRAN routine. A Makefile does the compiling 
and linking.

All the following files are in /u/postdoc/russ/random_field/

The FORTRAN routine passes top the C routine: 
 the number of rows,
 the number of columns,
 an array of two thetas (SDs),
 an array of 400,000 random numbers between 0 and 1. 
The FORTRAN routine receives back:
 an array with the gaussian random field in row order,
 a return value flag which should equal zero.

Here is the FORTRAN routine "generate_grf.f":

      program generate_grf
c "USE IFPORT" is so rand() works in this example
      USE IFPORT
c "EXTERNAL grf" is needed to properly link the C subroutine grf_
      EXTERNAL grf
      integer max_rand_count 
      integer rows,columns,ret_val
      parameter (max_rand_count=400000)
      parameter (rows=40)
      parameter (columns=64)
      double precision theta(2)
      double precision, allocatable :: R(:),gaussianrandomfield(:)
      allocate (R(max_rand_count),gaussianrandomfield(rows*columns))
      theta(1)=6.
      theta(2)=2.
      
      do 5 i=1,max_rand_count
        R(i)=rand()
 5    continue

      call grf(rows,columns,theta,R,gaussianrandomfield,ret_val)
      do 10 i=1,rows
        do 20 j=1,columns
          write(*,*) i,j,gaussianrandomfield((i-1)*columns+j)
 20     continue
        write(*,*) ''
 10   continue
      write(*,*) 'DONE',ret_val
      stop    
      end program

Here is the C subroutine "grf.c":

