Turns out that the algorithm which calculates the Matern
GRF can only generate fields with a maximum of 19,600 cells 
(e.g. 140x140). (This may be a glitch in the original code, because
the code uses the standard fftw library which can handle giant 
ffts.)

Also, it generates a matrix using one x,y size and extracts
the upper-left corner and returns that as the GRF. If the
dimensions specified for the return matrix are not the same as
the dimensions for the "generating" matrix, then there's a chance
that the first and last rows/columns will be correlated (depending
on the theta values).

For square matrices, valid theta1/theta2 pairs trace (roughly)
a y=16/x function.

For rectangular matrices, the valid theta1/theta2 pairs
are a ~1/x function with some x or y offset and cutoff at the
x/y axes.

