Code for 2-d complex fft in fortran:

https://software.intel.com/en-us/node/471390

fft2_complex.f90

The above is in Fortran 90. Need a Fortran 77 version.

This provides clues for a Fortran 77 version and a fftw version
called from Intel Fortran:

https://software.intel.com/en-us/articles/the-intel-math-kernel-library-and-its-fast-fourier-transform-routines

The example at the above page is for a 1-dimensional FFT.

This page reveals how to use an f90 file in F77: just compile it.

http://www.ch.cam.ac.uk/computing/software/intel-math-kernel-library

"Intel completely changed the way you use FFT somewhere between 
versions 7 and 9 of the library. To use them from Fortran under 
version 9 and above you need to copy the $MKLINCLUDE/mkl_dfti.f90 
file into your Fortran project and compile it (ifort -c mkl_dfti.f90) 
so you can then use the module (USE MKL_DFTI) in your own code."

Thus, one can use the mkl_dfti.f90 if one first compiles it
into mkl_dfti.o and then links it in to the F77 program. Remove the

include '/opt/intel/Compiler/11.1/064/mkl/include/mkl_dfti.f90'

line, and "USE MKL_DFTI" is adequate.

So now we have 

fft2_complex.f, which is in Fortran 77. Compile mkl_dfti.f90
(on eccles) like so: 

ifort -ipo -c /opt/intel/Compiler/11.1/064/mkl/include/mkl_dfti.f90

...this creates:

mkl_dft_type.mod
mkl_dfti.mod
mkl_dfti.o

(We need the .mod files and the .o or the compile/link below won't work.)

...then compile/link fft2_complex.f and mkl_dfti.o:

ifc4 mkl_dfti.o fft2_complex.f

This produces an a.out which runs.

