Created Gaussian Random Field generator via Circulant embedding
in Fortran:

/u/postdoc/russ/random_field/circulant_grf.f

...derived from Section 2.2 of

https://people.smp.uq.edu.au/DirkKroese/ps/MCSpatial.pdf

The .f90 library 
/opt/intel/Compiler/11.1/064/mkl/include/mkl_dfti.f90

is needed to use the MKL Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT)
in the MKL libraries. Our Fortran 77 format does not like the above,
so you need to 

ifort -ipo -c /opt/intel/Compiler/11.1/064/mkl/include/mkl_dfti.f90

...this creates:

mkl_dft_type.mod
mkl_dfti.mod
mkl_dfti.o

...in your local directory.

We need the .mod files and the .o or the compile/link below won't work.

Then compile/link circulant_grf.f and mkl_dfti.o:

ifc4 mkl_dfti.o circulant_grf.f

This produces an a.out which runs once through the algorithm
and produces two 100x160 arrays in fort.48 and fort.49 (for
testing purposes - ordered by column).

Note that most of the circulant_grf.f routine calculates the 
FFT-converted kernel called 'LAM' which is a constant for all 
subsequent GRF calculations (assuming the number of rows, columns, 
and standard deviations remain the same). I've written these 
comments to show where the one-time code is:

ccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccc
c   The following only needs to be done once.   c
c   It generates 'LAM' which is then used to    c
c   multiply against complex random numbers     c
c   then FFT'd to generate the random fields.   c
ccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccc

...LAM is calculated here...

ccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccc
c  End of section where LAM is calculated.  c
c  Pass LAM to the parallel section which   c
c  includes the following code. Only        c
c  calculate the following code once        c
c  for every two steps (odd numbered steps  c
c  use F1; even numbered steps use F2).     c
ccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccc

Note also that the "kernel" has a similar form to the gaussian 
process (from the file circulant.m, which was copied from
Section 2.2 above):

% These are the standard deviations in the x and y dimensions

s1=15;s2=15;

% This is the function which populates the circulant matrix

rho=@(x,y)((1-x^2/s2^2-x*y/(s1*s2)-y^2/s1^2)...
*exp(-(x^2/s2^2+y^2/s1^2)));

% These are the basis of values passed to rho

tx=[0:n-1]; ty=[0:m-1]; % create grid for field

% Rows and Cols go into the circular matrix

Rows=zeros(m,n); Cols=Rows;

for i=1:n
for j=1:m
Rows(j,i)=rho(tx(i)-tx(1),ty(j)-ty(1)); % rows of blocks
Cols(j,i)=rho(tx(1)-tx(i),ty(j)-ty(1)); % columns
end
end


